commit.message: Recognize _winapi as stdlib

Update the Python versions tested

3.4 has reached EOL, and 3.8 has been released.
Bump and release 0.18.1

Fix warning in noqa regexp

Regular expression for finding `# noqa` comments produces `DeprecationWarning: invalid escape sequence \s` when installing flake8-import-order as a requirement in setup.py. This line also fails `pycodestyle` check with message `W605 - invalid escape sequence '\s'`.
Environment to reproduce - python3.7, setuptools 39.0.1.

Remove deprecated ``sudo: false`` from .travis.yml

See https://blog.travis-ci.com/2018-11-19-required-linux-infrastructure-migration

Fix case-sensitive related I100 errors for the pycharm style.

Pycharm sorts imports over multiple line case-sensitive.
The following should be a valid import order.

  import B
  import a

Also added a pycharm test case.

Closes-issue: #158
Bump to 0.18

Add Python 3.7 CI testing

This requires a more complex travis.yml as 3.7 is not supported in the
default image (as yet). Therefore xenial is used and requires sudo
(I'm not sure why).
Update stdlib list for Python 3.7
Bump to 0.17.1
Make noqa more specific
Use set-literal instead of function
Bump to 0.17
feat: implement PyCharm import style
Fix minor typo

Alter edited style definition

The relative import and application imports should not be considered
the same section.

Allow styles an ability to override the actual checks

This is specifically helpful to allow the edited style to have an
optional newline between ``import`` and ``form X import`` lines
without triggering a I202 error.

In a more general sense this should allow for more advanced styles.

Further update import explanation

This should make the full import clearer (as it is now fully
reported), as well as continue the lazy evaluation.

Lazily build grouping explanation string

The previous logic would build the grouping explanation string for every
import, even if there isn't an error condition. This was unnecessary, so
we now defer that formatting work to a static method that is only
invoked when an error is detected.

Also, change the second `if` to an `elif` because these cases can't both
be true at the same time.

Return parsed codes as a set()

We can directly use a set comprehension here instead of building and
returning an intermediate list.
Use enumerate(..., start=1) to generate lineno
Use ImportType.MIXED instead of -1

Simplify re group access

`.group(name)` is more straightforward than `.groupdict()[name]`.
Add _threading_local to the stdlib list

Improve the error messages and typing

This hopefully makes the errors clearer to the user, thereby allowing
them to better understand how to fix the error. As it explains the
sections determined and will note if the section is wrong when
considering the relative ordering.

This also uses a Enum for convenience, which in turn improves the type
usage.

Remove all but root packages

`:g/\./d`
Add `encodings` and `xmlrpc`

Add remaining python3 modules

I've noted a couple missing packages, so today I wanted to see if I could get the remainder. I have the html version of the 3.6.3 docs downloaded locally for quick reference, so I figured this would be an easy to scrape most of the missing modules.

I wrote a quick script to import the scraped modules in a fresh venv to make sure all of these are importable and hopefully eliminate any false positives. I used a combination of the below strategies, all of which were run from `python-3.6.3-docs-html/library`

Collect the HTML filenames, which for the most part seem to be importable modules, and if they are importable and not in `stdlib.txt` (a text file of flake8-import-order's existing stdlib list), then accumulate them:
```shell_session
for htmlfile in *.html; do lib="${htmlfile%.html}"; if ! grep --quiet "${lib}" stdlib.txt; then python3 -c "import ${lib}" &> /dev/null && echo "${lib}" >> good_imports.txt; fi; done
```

Scrape the HTML files for any `<div>` with an `id` starting with `module-`:
```shell_session
$ grep -h -P -o '(?<=<div class="section" id="module-).*(?=">)' *.html | sort -u > all_modules.txt
```

Try to import each module; accumulate the ones that work and print the ones that result in an error.
```shell_session
$ for lib in $(cat all_modules.txt); do python3 -c "import ${lib}" &> /dev/null && echo "${lib}" >> good_imports.txt || echo "${lib}"; done
```

Then I just basically did a `sort --unique` with the existing stdlib list.

Anyway, may want to look it over to make sure I didn't screw something up, but I think that having tested for import-ability in a fresh venv should mean all the additions are valid.
